{"title_page": "Andrew Thompson (priest)", "text_new": "{{Infobox religious biography\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name             = Andrew Thompson\n| honorific-suffix = [[MBE (Order of the British Empire)|MBE]]\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image            = Reverend Canon Andrew Thompson at St Andrew\u2019s Church Abu Dhabi.jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Reverend Canon Andrew Thompson at St Andrew\u2019s Church in Abu Dhabi, UAE\n| religion         = [[Anglicanism|Anglican]]\n| denomination     = [[Anglicanism|Anglican]]\n| school           = \n| lineage          = \n| sect             = \n| subsect          = \n| temple           = \n| order            = \n| institute        =\n| church           = St Andrew's Church,<ref name=standrewauh/> [[Abu Dhabi]], [[United Arab Emirates]]\n| founder          =\n| philosophy       =\n| known_for        =\n| education        = [[Heart of England School]]\n| alma_mater       = [[Polytechnic of Wales]]\n| other_names      = <!-- or: | other_name = -->\n| dharma_names     = <!-- or: | dharma_name = -->\n| monastic_name    = \n| pen_name         = \n| posthumous_name  = \n| nationality      = English\n| flourished       =\n| home_town        = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1968|06|23|df=y}} \n| birth_place      = [[Crawley]]\n| death_date       = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| death_place      = \n| death_cause      =\n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|latitude|longitude|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n| spouse           = Navina\n| partner          =\n| children         = 3\n| parents          = \n| mother           =\n| father           =\n| location         = \n| title            = \n| period           = \n| consecration     = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| reason           = \n| rank             = \n| teacher          = <!-- or | guru = -->\n| reincarnation_of = \n| students         = <!-- or | disciples = -->\n| initiated        =\n| works            = <!-- or | literary_works = -->\n| ordination       = June 2000\n| initiation       = \n| initiation_date  =\n| initiation_place =\n| initiator        =\n| profession       = Author, magician and interfaith activist\n| previous_post    = \n| present_post     = \n| post             = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| signature        = \n| background       = <!-- optional header background color -->\n}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=November 2019}}\n{{Orphan|date=December 2019}}\n}}\n\n'''Andrew Thompson''' (born 23 June 1968) is an English [[Anglican priest|Anglican Priest]], currently based at St Andrew's Church,<ref name=standrewauh>{{cite web|url=http://standrewauh.org/|title=St Andrew's Anglican Church|website=St Andrew's Anglican Church|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> [[Abu Dhabi]], [[United Arab Emirates]], he is also an author, magician and interfaith activist.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nThompson was born in [[Crawley]] and went to the Heart of England school in Balsall Common; he was born with a [[hearing impairment]], which affected his speech. His parents were both officers in the [[Church Army]], an [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] organisation which provides [[Evangelism|evangelists]] for the [[Church of England]] and other places in the [[Anglican Communion]]. He studied [[Behavioural Sciences]] at the Polytechnic of Wales (now the [[University of Glamorgan]]).\n\n== Ministry ==\nAfter graduating, he spent several years working with churches in the [[Middle East]] and [[North Africa]]. He then returned to the UK and served as a Youth Worker at [[Holy Trinity Church, Matlock Bath]] in the [[Diocese of Derby]]. During this time, he developed his skills in [[Magic (illusion)|magic]] and used this as a teaching tool for the [[Christianity|Christian faith]] and released his first book; Gospel Magic for Preachers.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Gospel-Magic-Tricks-Visual-Evangelism/dp/1851744819|title=Gospel Magic: How to Use Magic Tricks as Visual Aids (Evangelism S.)|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2001/decemberweb-only/22.0a.html |title=Let Harry Potter Conjure Up 'Gospel Magic', Says Christian Magician |publisher=Christianity Today |date=2001-12-01 |accessdate=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n\nHe was [[Ordination#Roman Catholic, Orthodox, and Anglican churches|ordained]] in [[Derby Cathedral]] by [[Jonathan Bailey (bishop)|Jonathan Bailey]] in June 2000. He served his curacy at the Oakwood Ecumenical Church<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thechurchonoakwood.org/|title=Welcome to The Church on Oakwood {{!}} The Church on Oakwood|website=www.thechurchonoakwood.org|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> from 2000 \u2013 2004, while studying for a [[Master's Degree]] from the [[University of Nottingham]], in which he studied the [[Muslim]] community of [[Derby]] and issues of [[Identity (philosophy)|identity]], [[theology]] and [[Cultural assimilation|cultural integration]].\n\nHe then returned to the [[Middle East]], where he was the [[chaplain]] at St Paul\u2019s Church, in Kuwait from 2006 \u2013 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stpaulskuwait.com/|title=Saint Paul's Church of Kuwait|last=contentmgr|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> and was made an [[Canon (priest)|Honorary Canon]] of Bahrain Cathedral.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/dec/31/reality-of-being-christian-in-the-gulf|title=The reality of being a Christian in the Gulf {{!}} Letter: Rev Canon Andy Thompson|last=Staff|first=Guardian|date=2014-12-31|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-07-19|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bahraincathedral.org/|title=Welcome to the Cathedral of Our Lady of Arabia, Bahrain|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> He sparked [[controversy]] when a newspaper article recorded a statement, in which he declared that it \u201cwas easier to be a Christian in the UAE than in the UK\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/its-easier-being-christian-in-abu-dhabi-than-in-uk-1.1330220|title=\u2018It\u2019s easier being Christian in Abu Dhabi than in UK\u2019|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Khashan|first=Hilal|date=2016-06-01|title=Religious Intolerance in the Gulf States|url=https://www.meforum.org/6044/religious-intolerance-in-the-gulf-states|journal=Middle East Quarterly|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://website.aub.edu.lb/main/Documents/Gulf-Christians.pdf|title=Christianity's Claim in the Birthplace of Islam|last=Khashan|first=Hilal|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.catholicfocus.in/dubai-an-oasis-of-christian-faith/|title=DUBAI \u2013 An Oasis of Christian Faith|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThis statement was subsequently used by the UAE ambassador to the USA in support of the tolerant ethos his country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2015/12/02/a-vision-for-a-moderate-modern-muslim-world-uae-abu-dhabi-isis/|title=A Vision for a Moderate, Modern Muslim World|last=Otaiba|first=Yousef Al|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Thompson became the chaplain at St Andrew\u2019s Church, [[Abu Dhabi]], [[United Arab Emirates]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://standrewauh.org/about-us/our-chaplain/|title=St. Andrew's Church - Our Chaplain|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> this church is part of the [[Diocese of Cyprus and the Gulf]].\n\n== Interfaith work ==\nThompson is chairman of the board for the Al Amana Centre,<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=http://alamanacentre.org/about/|title=Our People / Our Centre \u2013 Al Amana Centre|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> which is in [[Muscat]], [[Oman]]. This is the only [[Christianity and Islam|muslim-christian relations]] interfaith institute run by the church in the [[Arabian Peninsula]], the centre provides [[scriptural reasoning]] and other [[Interfaith dialogue|interfaith encounters]] between visiting groups of christian students, pastors, scholars and local [[Islam in Oman|Omani muslims]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://alamanacentre.org/what-we-provide/|title=What We Provide \u2013 Al Amana Centre|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nHe has had the opportunity to promote a better understanding of life for christians in the [[Arab states of the Persian Gulf|Persian Gulf region]], in various contexts, including at the [[House of Lords]] in London,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christiansinparliament.org.uk/events/past-events/christians-in-the-middle-east-a-different-perspective |title=Christians in the Middle East: A Different Perspective \u2013 Christians in Parliament |publisher=Christiansinparliament.org.uk |date=2015-11-02 |accessdate=2019-11-19}}</ref> the [[G20]] Interfaith Summit in Australia,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.g20interfaith.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/2014-Speakers-Special-Guests-_-G20-Interfaith-Forum.pdf|title=G20 Interfaith Forum - 2014 Speakers & Special Guests|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> he has spoken at the Doha Trialogues,<ref>[http://www.dicid.org/english/docs/12th_conference_proceedings_en.pdf ]{{dead link|date=November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://qatarconferences.org/interfaith2011/speech10.php|title=9th Doha Conference of Inter-Faith Dialogue|website=qatarconferences.org|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> in [[Folketing|Parliament in Denmark]],<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|url=http://wam.ae/en/details/1395296259818|title=Sheikha Lubna makes the case for tolerance|website=wam|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> and met Pope Francis in the Vatican as part of a delegation from the [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref name=\"auto3\"/> He has also attended the [[National Prayer Breakfast]] in [[Washington, D.C.]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wam.ae/en/details/1395302595603|title=UAE Minister of Tolerance attends National Prayer Breakfast in Washington, DC|website=wam|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> and the Religious Pluralism Conference in [[Athens]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mfa.gr/missionsabroad/en/uae-en/news/2nd-athens-conference-on-religious-and-cultural-pluralism-and-peaceful-coexistence-in-the-middle-east-30-31102017.html|title=2nd Athens Conference on Religious and Cultural Pluralism and Peaceful Coexistence in the Middle East (30-31.10.2017) - Embassy News|website=www.mfa.gr|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> as a representative of the Christian community in the [[United Arab Emirates]].\n\n==Honours==\nThompson was awarded an [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] in 2011, for his \"services to human rights and promoting interfaith dialogue between Christians and Muslims in Kuwait\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/honours-list/8231975/New-Year-Honours-List-2011-in-full.html|title=New Year Honours List 2011 in full|date=2010-12-31|access-date=2019-07-19|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n== Books ==\n'''''Jesus of Arabia'''''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.booksarabia.com/jesus-of-arabia.html|title=Booksarabia.com - Jesus of Arabia|website=www.booksarabia.com|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\n''Jesus of Arabia'' explores the teachings of [[Jesus]] through the culture of the [[Persian Gulf]] region, the book has received favourable reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/opinion/what-jesus-of-arabia-says-about-the-modern-day-uae-1.111486|title=What Jesus of Arabia says about the modern-day UAE|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/abu-dhabi-minister-hopes-to-foster-interfaith-dialogue-with-jesus-of-arabia-1.450137|title=Abu Dhabi minister hopes to foster interfaith dialogue with \u2018Jesus of Arabia\u2019|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/44356390-jesus-of-arabia|title=Jesus of Arabia|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> and has been translated into [[Arabic]].\n\n'''''Christianity in the United Arab Emirates'''''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.booksarabia.com/books/life-in-arabia/christianity-in-the-uae.html|title=Booksarabia.com - Christianity in the UAE - Life in Arabia - Books|website=www.booksarabia.com|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\nThis book considers the history and significance of the christian faith in the [[United Arab Emirates]], the author discusses the increasing importance of Muslim-Christian relations in enabling [[international security]], he calls for and gives examples of bridge building activities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/books/book-review-thompson-offers-a-solid-insight-on-uae-s-christian-community-1.577324|title=Book review: Thompson offers a solid insight on UAE's Christian community|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> The book launch was hosted by the [[List of ambassadors of the United Kingdom to the United Arab Emirates|British Ambassador to the UAE]], Dominic Jermey and was attended by [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York]] and [[Nahyan bin Mubarak Al Nahyan|Sheikh Nahyan bin Mubarak Al Nahyan]], the Minister of Culture for the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/queen-sends-national-day-message-1.937229|title=Queen sends National Day message|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\n'''''The Christian Church in Kuwait'''''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Christian-Church-Kuwait-Religious-Freedom/dp/9990698724|title=The Christian Church in Kuwait, Religious Freedom in the Gulf|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''''Gospel Magic for Preachers: Theology & Praxis'''''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blessedhope-publishing.com/catalog/details//store/hu/book/978-3-639-50006-6/gospel-magic-for-preachers|title=Gospel Magic for Preachers / 978-3-639-50006-6 / 9783639500066 / 3639500067|website=www.blessedhope-publishing.com|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> \u00a0\n\n'''''Gospel Magic. How to use Magic Tricks as Visual Aids'''''<ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2001/decemberweb-only/22.0a.html|title=Let Harry Potter Conjure Up 'Gospel Magic', Says Christian Magician|last=Pulford|first=Cedric|website=ChristianityToday.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\n== Films ==\nThompson has been the subject of two films:\n\n'''''One.'''''\n\n''One.'' was directed and produced by Daniel Malak,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanadfilmfund.com/en/archive/2014/films-2014/film-details?ID=14998|title=One|website=Abu Dhabi Film Festival|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=DanMalak|title=One (Religious Tolerance in the UAE) {{!}} (\u0648\u0627\u062d\u062f (\u0627\u0644\u062a\u0633\u0627\u0645\u062d \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0645\u0627\u0631\u0627\u062a|date=2014-12-25|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qq6Av0JTeCc|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> it is a short [[documentary]] based on the friendship and hope for religious tolerance between a [[priest]] and an [[imam]].\n\n'''''Hartom'''''\n\n''Hartom'' is a [[documentary]] written and directed by Arkus Arksus,<ref name=\"auto\">{{Citation|title=Hartom|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt6169284/|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> based on the professional life of Andrew Thompson.\n\nIt has been screened at various [[Film festival|film festivals]] and won the best producer award at the 2016 Arab Film studio<ref>{{cite web|url=https://imagenationabudhabi.com/en/media-center/press-releases/2016/image-nation-abu-dhabi-crowns-winners-of-coveted-arab-film-studio-programs/|title=Image Nation Abu Dhabi crowns winners of coveted Arab Film Studio programs|website=Image Nation Abu Dhabi|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>, as well as best documentary short at the 2017 Whatashort Independent International Film Festival in [[India]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n== Personal life ==\nThompson is married to Navina and they have three children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://standrewauh.org/about-us/our-chaplain/) |title=Our Chaplain - St Andrew's Anglican Church &#124; St Andrew's Centre &#124; Mushrif &#124; Abu Dhabi &#124; United Arab Emirates |publisher=Standrewauh.org |date= |accessdate=2019-11-19}}</ref> \u00a0\n\nHe is currently working towards a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PHD]] in [[Christianity and Islam|Muslim-Christian]] Relations in the Persian Gulf through the [[University of Gloucestershire]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thompson, Andrew}}\n\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century English Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:20th-century English Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:English magicians]]\n[[Category:English Anglican theologians]]\n[[Category:People from Crawley]]\n[[Category:People from Abu Dhabi]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Deaf religious workers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glamorgan]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Nottingham]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox religious biography\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name             = Andrew Thompson\n| honorific-suffix = [[MBE]]\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image            = Reverend Canon Andrew Thompson at St Andrew\u2019s Church Abu Dhabi.jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Reverend Canon Andrew Thompson at St Andrew\u2019s Church in Abu Dhabi, UAE\n| religion         = [[Anglicanism|Anglican]]\n| denomination     = [[Anglicanism|Anglican]]\n| school           = \n| lineage          = \n| sect             = \n| subsect          = \n| temple           = \n| order            = \n| institute        =\n| church           = St Andrew's Church,<ref name=standrewauh/> [[Abu Dhabi]], [[United Arab Emirates]]\n| founder          =\n| philosophy       =\n| known_for        =\n| education        = [[Heart of England School]]\n| alma_mater       = [[Polytechnic of Wales]]\n| other_names      = <!-- or: | other_name = -->\n| dharma_names     = <!-- or: | dharma_name = -->\n| monastic_name    = \n| pen_name         = \n| posthumous_name  = \n| nationality      = English\n| flourished       =\n| home_town        = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1968|06|23|df=y}} \n| birth_place      = [[Crawley]]\n| death_date       = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| death_place      = \n| death_cause      =\n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|latitude|longitude|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n| spouse           = Navina\n| partner          =\n| children         = 3\n| parents          = \n| mother           =\n| father           =\n| location         = \n| title            = \n| period           = \n| consecration     = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| reason           = \n| rank             = \n| teacher          = <!-- or | guru = -->\n| reincarnation_of = \n| students         = <!-- or | disciples = -->\n| initiated        =\n| works            = <!-- or | literary_works = -->\n| ordination       = June 2000\n| initiation       = \n| initiation_date  =\n| initiation_place =\n| initiator        =\n| profession       = Author, magician and interfaith activist\n| previous_post    = \n| present_post     = \n| post             = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| signature        = \n| background       = <!-- optional header background color -->\n}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=November 2019}}\n{{Orphan|date=December 2019}}\n}}\n\n'''Andrew Thompson''' (born 23 June 1968) is an English [[Anglican priest|Anglican Priest]], currently based at St Andrew's Church,<ref name=standrewauh>{{cite web|url=http://standrewauh.org/|title=St Andrew's Anglican Church|website=St Andrew's Anglican Church|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> [[Abu Dhabi]], [[United Arab Emirates]], he is also an author, magician and interfaith activist.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nThompson was born in [[Crawley]] and went to the Heart of England school in Balsall Common; he was born with a [[hearing impairment]], which affected his speech. His parents were both officers in the [[Church Army]], an [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] organisation which provides [[Evangelism|evangelists]] for the [[Church of England]] and other places in the [[Anglican Communion]]. He studied [[Behavioural Sciences]] at the Polytechnic of Wales (now the [[University of Glamorgan]]).\n\n== Ministry ==\nAfter graduating, he spent several years working with churches in the [[Middle East]] and [[North Africa]]. He then returned to the UK and served as a Youth Worker at [[Holy Trinity Church, Matlock Bath]] in the [[Diocese of Derby]]. During this time, he developed his skills in [[Magic (illusion)|magic]] and used this as a teaching tool for the [[Christianity|Christian faith]] and released his first book; Gospel Magic for Preachers.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Gospel-Magic-Tricks-Visual-Evangelism/dp/1851744819|title=Gospel Magic: How to Use Magic Tricks as Visual Aids (Evangelism S.)|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2001/decemberweb-only/22.0a.html |title=Let Harry Potter Conjure Up 'Gospel Magic', Says Christian Magician |publisher=Christianity Today |date=2001-12-01 |accessdate=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n\nHe was [[Ordination#Roman Catholic, Orthodox, and Anglican churches|ordained]] in [[Derby Cathedral]] by [[Jonathan Bailey (bishop)|Jonathan Bailey]] in June 2000. He served his curacy at the Oakwood Ecumenical Church<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thechurchonoakwood.org/|title=Welcome to The Church on Oakwood {{!}} The Church on Oakwood|website=www.thechurchonoakwood.org|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> from 2000 \u2013 2004, while studying for a [[Master's Degree]] from the [[University of Nottingham]], in which he studied the [[Muslim]] community of [[Derby]] and issues of [[Identity (philosophy)|identity]], [[theology]] and [[Cultural assimilation|cultural integration]].\n\nHe then returned to the [[Middle East]], where he was the [[chaplain]] at St Paul\u2019s Church, in Kuwait from 2006 \u2013 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stpaulskuwait.com/|title=Saint Paul's Church of Kuwait|last=contentmgr|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> and was made an [[Canon (priest)|Honorary Canon]] of Bahrain Cathedral.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/dec/31/reality-of-being-christian-in-the-gulf|title=The reality of being a Christian in the Gulf {{!}} Letter: Rev Canon Andy Thompson|last=Staff|first=Guardian|date=2014-12-31|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-07-19|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bahraincathedral.org/|title=Welcome to the Cathedral of Our Lady of Arabia, Bahrain|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> He sparked [[controversy]] when a newspaper article recorded a statement, in which he declared that it \u201cwas easier to be a Christian in the UAE than in the UK\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/its-easier-being-christian-in-abu-dhabi-than-in-uk-1.1330220|title=\u2018It\u2019s easier being Christian in Abu Dhabi than in UK\u2019|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Khashan|first=Hilal|date=2016-06-01|title=Religious Intolerance in the Gulf States|url=https://www.meforum.org/6044/religious-intolerance-in-the-gulf-states|journal=Middle East Quarterly|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://website.aub.edu.lb/main/Documents/Gulf-Christians.pdf|title=Christianity's Claim in the Birthplace of Islam|last=Khashan|first=Hilal|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.catholicfocus.in/dubai-an-oasis-of-christian-faith/|title=DUBAI \u2013 An Oasis of Christian Faith|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThis statement was subsequently used by the UAE ambassador to the USA in support of the tolerant ethos his country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2015/12/02/a-vision-for-a-moderate-modern-muslim-world-uae-abu-dhabi-isis/|title=A Vision for a Moderate, Modern Muslim World|last=Otaiba|first=Yousef Al|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Thompson became the chaplain at St Andrew\u2019s Church, [[Abu Dhabi]], [[United Arab Emirates]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://standrewauh.org/about-us/our-chaplain/|title=St. Andrew's Church - Our Chaplain|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> this church is part of the [[Diocese of Cyprus and the Gulf]].\n\n== Interfaith work ==\nThompson is chairman of the board for the Al Amana Centre,<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=http://alamanacentre.org/about/|title=Our People / Our Centre \u2013 Al Amana Centre|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> which is in [[Muscat]], [[Oman]]. This is the only [[Christianity and Islam|muslim-christian relations]] interfaith institute run by the church in the [[Arabian Peninsula]], the centre provides [[scriptural reasoning]] and other [[Interfaith dialogue|interfaith encounters]] between visiting groups of christian students, pastors, scholars and local [[Islam in Oman|Omani muslims]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://alamanacentre.org/what-we-provide/|title=What We Provide \u2013 Al Amana Centre|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nHe has had the opportunity to promote a better understanding of life for christians in the [[Arab states of the Persian Gulf|Persian Gulf region]], in various contexts, including at the [[House of Lords]] in London,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christiansinparliament.org.uk/events/past-events/christians-in-the-middle-east-a-different-perspective |title=Christians in the Middle East: A Different Perspective \u2013 Christians in Parliament |publisher=Christiansinparliament.org.uk |date=2015-11-02 |accessdate=2019-11-19}}</ref> the [[G20]] Interfaith Summit in Australia,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.g20interfaith.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/2014-Speakers-Special-Guests-_-G20-Interfaith-Forum.pdf|title=G20 Interfaith Forum - 2014 Speakers & Special Guests|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> he has spoken at the Doha Trialogues,<ref>[http://www.dicid.org/english/docs/12th_conference_proceedings_en.pdf ]{{dead link|date=November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://qatarconferences.org/interfaith2011/speech10.php|title=9th Doha Conference of Inter-Faith Dialogue|website=qatarconferences.org|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> in [[Folketing|Parliament in Denmark]],<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|url=http://wam.ae/en/details/1395296259818|title=Sheikha Lubna makes the case for tolerance|website=wam|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> and met Pope Francis in the Vatican as part of a delegation from the [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref name=\"auto3\"/> He has also attended the [[National Prayer Breakfast]] in [[Washington, D.C.]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wam.ae/en/details/1395302595603|title=UAE Minister of Tolerance attends National Prayer Breakfast in Washington, DC|website=wam|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> and the Religious Pluralism Conference in [[Athens]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mfa.gr/missionsabroad/en/uae-en/news/2nd-athens-conference-on-religious-and-cultural-pluralism-and-peaceful-coexistence-in-the-middle-east-30-31102017.html|title=2nd Athens Conference on Religious and Cultural Pluralism and Peaceful Coexistence in the Middle East (30-31.10.2017) - Embassy News|website=www.mfa.gr|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> as a representative of the Christian community in the [[United Arab Emirates]].\n\n==Honours==\nThompson was awarded an [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] in 2011, for his \"services to human rights and promoting interfaith dialogue between Christians and Muslims in Kuwait\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/honours-list/8231975/New-Year-Honours-List-2011-in-full.html|title=New Year Honours List 2011 in full|date=2010-12-31|access-date=2019-07-19|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n== Books ==\n'''''Jesus of Arabia'''''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.booksarabia.com/jesus-of-arabia.html|title=Booksarabia.com - Jesus of Arabia|website=www.booksarabia.com|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\n''Jesus of Arabia'' explores the teachings of [[Jesus]] through the culture of the [[Persian Gulf]] region, the book has received favourable reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/opinion/what-jesus-of-arabia-says-about-the-modern-day-uae-1.111486|title=What Jesus of Arabia says about the modern-day UAE|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/abu-dhabi-minister-hopes-to-foster-interfaith-dialogue-with-jesus-of-arabia-1.450137|title=Abu Dhabi minister hopes to foster interfaith dialogue with \u2018Jesus of Arabia\u2019|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/44356390-jesus-of-arabia|title=Jesus of Arabia|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> and has been translated into [[Arabic]].\n\n'''''Christianity in the United Arab Emirates'''''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.booksarabia.com/books/life-in-arabia/christianity-in-the-uae.html|title=Booksarabia.com - Christianity in the UAE - Life in Arabia - Books|website=www.booksarabia.com|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\nThis book considers the history and significance of the christian faith in the [[United Arab Emirates]], the author discusses the increasing importance of Muslim-Christian relations in enabling [[international security]], he calls for and gives examples of bridge building activities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/books/book-review-thompson-offers-a-solid-insight-on-uae-s-christian-community-1.577324|title=Book review: Thompson offers a solid insight on UAE's Christian community|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> The book launch was hosted by the [[List of ambassadors of the United Kingdom to the United Arab Emirates|British Ambassador to the UAE]], Dominic Jermey and was attended by [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York]] and [[Nahyan bin Mubarak Al Nahyan|Sheikh Nahyan bin Mubarak Al Nahyan]], the Minister of Culture for the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/queen-sends-national-day-message-1.937229|title=Queen sends National Day message|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\n'''''The Christian Church in Kuwait'''''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Christian-Church-Kuwait-Religious-Freedom/dp/9990698724|title=The Christian Church in Kuwait, Religious Freedom in the Gulf|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''''Gospel Magic for Preachers: Theology & Praxis'''''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blessedhope-publishing.com/catalog/details//store/hu/book/978-3-639-50006-6/gospel-magic-for-preachers|title=Gospel Magic for Preachers / 978-3-639-50006-6 / 9783639500066 / 3639500067|website=www.blessedhope-publishing.com|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> \u00a0\n\n'''''Gospel Magic. How to use Magic Tricks as Visual Aids'''''<ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2001/decemberweb-only/22.0a.html|title=Let Harry Potter Conjure Up 'Gospel Magic', Says Christian Magician|last=Pulford|first=Cedric|website=ChristianityToday.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\n== Films ==\nThompson has been the subject of two films:\n\n'''''One.'''''\n\n''One.'' was directed and produced by Daniel Malak,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanadfilmfund.com/en/archive/2014/films-2014/film-details?ID=14998|title=One|website=Abu Dhabi Film Festival|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=DanMalak|title=One (Religious Tolerance in the UAE) {{!}} (\u0648\u0627\u062d\u062f (\u0627\u0644\u062a\u0633\u0627\u0645\u062d \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0645\u0627\u0631\u0627\u062a|date=2014-12-25|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qq6Av0JTeCc|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> it is a short [[documentary]] based on the friendship and hope for religious tolerance between a [[priest]] and an [[imam]].\n\n'''''Hartom'''''\n\n''Hartom'' is a [[documentary]] written and directed by Arkus Arksus,<ref name=\"auto\">{{Citation|title=Hartom|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt6169284/|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> based on the professional life of Andrew Thompson.\n\nIt has been screened at various [[Film festival|film festivals]] and won the best producer award at the 2016 Arab Film studio<ref>{{cite web|url=https://imagenationabudhabi.com/en/media-center/press-releases/2016/image-nation-abu-dhabi-crowns-winners-of-coveted-arab-film-studio-programs/|title=Image Nation Abu Dhabi crowns winners of coveted Arab Film Studio programs|website=Image Nation Abu Dhabi|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>, as well as best documentary short at the 2017 Whatashort Independent International Film Festival in [[India]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n== Personal life ==\nThompson is married to Navina and they have three children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://standrewauh.org/about-us/our-chaplain/) |title=Our Chaplain - St Andrew's Anglican Church &#124; St Andrew's Centre &#124; Mushrif &#124; Abu Dhabi &#124; United Arab Emirates |publisher=Standrewauh.org |date= |accessdate=2019-11-19}}</ref> \u00a0\n\nHe is currently working towards a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PHD]] in [[Christianity and Islam|Muslim-Christian]] Relations in the Persian Gulf through the [[University of Gloucestershire]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thompson, Andrew}}\n\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century English Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:20th-century English Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:English magicians]]\n[[Category:English Anglican theologians]]\n[[Category:People from Crawley]]\n[[Category:People from Abu Dhabi]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Deaf religious workers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glamorgan]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Nottingham]]\n", "name_user": "Paradoctor", "label": "safe", "comment": "dab", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrew_Thompson_(priest)"}
